sourceQuestion:
A sink in a directed graph is a vertex i such that there is an edge from every vertex j (j != i) to i and there is no edge from i to any other vertex. A directed graph G with n vertices is represented by its adjacency matrix A, where A[j][k] = 1 if there is an edge directed from vertex j to k and A[j][k] = 0 otherwise. The following algorithm determines whether there is a sink in the graph G.

i = 1;
j = 1;
while (j <= n) {
  if (E1) flag = false;
  else if (E2) flag = false;
  else { i = j; flag = true; }
  j = j + 1;
}

if (flag) output("Sink is", i);
else output("No Sink");

Choose the correct expressions for E1 and E2.

A. E1: A[i][j] and E2: A[j][i], i = j
B. E1: A[i][j] and E2: A[j][i], i != j
C. E1: !A[i][j] and E2: A[j][i], i = j
D. E1: A[i][j] and E2: !A[j][i], i = j

